<br>
First off, it's pronounced so-AIN.  Samhain is the Druidic New Year, the day that marks the ending of the Season of Life and the beginning of the Season of Sleep (Druids' years had only two sections, basically Summer and Winter).  Samhain marked the last harvest before Winter came.<br>
<br>
Because the night of Samhain is at once an ending and a beginning, the Druids saw it as a magic time when the veil between the worlds of the living and the dead was thin.  Activities included telling stories of family history, attempting to contact lost ancestors, and performing spellwork for protection against harm.<br>
<br>
Because of its association with the thinning of the veil, Samhain survived the Druid culture and came down through time as the Feast of the Dead.  Ancient post-druidic people wore costumes to keep the dead from recognizing them -- so there'd be no chance the dead would try to drag them through the veil to the other side.<br>
<br>
Is this sounding at all familiar yet?  Yes, Halloween!  The Druidic Samhain holiday was celebrated sometime around the first week of November, but over time it was moved back to October 31st so it would coincide with a Christian feast day.  Traditional Halloween activities reflect both the harvest theme (bobbing for apples) and the thinning of the veil (costumes, jack-o-lanterns, etc).<br>
<br>
